We are getting an error that is interrupting the schedule import.  It occurs in a few of the rows of the schedule on the cost2 column.  There is a formula for that column that is sometimes returning a non-zero number with lots of decimal places.  On import, that number is being represented in scientific notation even though it is being displayed in Microsoft Project as $0.00.
(e.g. the cost2 column of task “Implement Phase 2” is coming in as “-7.275957614183426E-12” instead of “-0.000000000007275957614183426”)

As a fix, we can change the line in DataEditorApi.cs
from: row[att.Key] = Convert.ToDecimal(att.Value.valueAsString);
to:     row[att.Key] = Decimal.Parse(att.Value.valueAsString, System.Globalization.NumberStyles.Float);

As a workaround for our General Dynamics customer who cannot import their schedule now, I have suggested that they round their cost2 column (which is the one with the scientific notation) to two decimal places with using Round(TheirOldFormulaText, 2) which will allow them to import before our fix has been fielded

